Oishi examines the cross-national patterns of international female migration in Asia. Drawing on fieldwork in ten countries—both migrant-sending and migrant-receiving—the author investigates the differential impact of globalization, state policies, individual autonomy, and various social factors. This is the first study of its kind to provide an integrative approach to and a comparative perspective on female migration flows from multiple countries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMigration, InternalxAsia. 0aMigration, InternalzAsia. 0aWomen foreign workersxAsia. 0aWomen foreign workerszAsia. 0aWomen in developmentxAsia. 0aWomen in developmentzAsia. 0aWomen's rightsxAsia. 0aWomen's rightszAsia. 4aSociology -- Global Issues, Economy, and Work. 4aSociology -- Immigration. 4aSociology -- Race, Class, and Gender. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107042040 cprintz978080474637340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476690640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804766906423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804766906/original  a978-3-11-070420-4  Stanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles